{
  "doc_id": "51628",
  "text": "The concept of total mesorectal excision (TME), introduced by Professor Bill Heald (father of TME) [CITATION_1] , significantly reduces the rate of local recurrence of rectal cancer. Recent randomized clinical trials (RCTs) have demonstrated better results for laparoscopic TME (laTME) in terms of short-and long-term oncological outcomes, when compared with open TME [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . However, obesity presents both negative and positive challenges to laparoscopic rectal surgery: the laparoscopic procedure becomes more technically demanding; on the other hand, the laparoscopic approach may be particularly advantageous to obese patients, resulting in reduced postoperative pain, faster postoperative recovery, and shorter hospital stay [CITATION_5] .",
